==English==

===Noun===
# A pace-egg or [[paste-egg]] is a hard boiled coloured egg traditionally made at [[Easter]], often given to relatives and friends as a token of goodwill.  The term was in common use in the North-East of England at least until the 1960s.  The colouring was often done by boiling the egg in onion skins.  Its etymology may have something to do with Dutch or Norse words for Easter, Pasen or Påsk.  It was traditional to [[jarp]] with the eggs before eating them.

